"Ter Hofstede R., Rijnsdorp A.D.","Comparing demersal fish assemblages between periods of contrasting climate and fishing pressure",2011,"ICES Journal of Marine Science","68","6",,"1189","1198",,,10.1093/icesjms/fsr053,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959492760&partnerID=40&md5=dbc532f8216e00920c6ee99b96308062","IMARESInstitute for Marine Resources and Ecosystem Studies, PO Box 68, 1970 AB IJmuiden, Netherlands","Ter Hofstede, R., IMARESInstitute for Marine Resources and Ecosystem Studies, PO Box 68, 1970 AB IJmuiden, Netherlands; Rijnsdorp, A.D., IMARESInstitute for Marine Resources and Ecosystem Studies, PO Box 68, 1970 AB IJmuiden, Netherlands","Fish communities are dynamic and their structure is known to change over time. Traditionally, these changes were considered to be fisheries-induced, but recent analyses also suggest that global warming could affect the distribution, abundance, and assemblage composition of marine fish. However, disentangling the effects of fisheries and those resulting from climate change is difficult, because both potential drivers act simultaneously. In our study, we distinguished between the effects of fisheries and climate change on the fish assemblage of the southern North Sea by comparing survey catch data for that region during four unique periods throughout the past century, characterized by (i) low fishing pressure during a cold period (19021908), (ii) low fishing pressure during a warm period (19501956), (iii) high fishing pressure during a cold period (19781984), and (iv) high fishing pressure during a warm period (20022008). Our analysis indicates that the demersal fish community in the southern North Sea has changed in response to changes in both climate and fishing pressure. Our results suggest both a relatively higher richness of Lusitanian (warm-favouring) species compared with boreal (cool-favouring) species, and a lower mean body size of the fish community during times of warming, independent of fishing pressure. © 2011 International Council for the Exploration of the Sea.","biogeography; body size; climate change; fisheries; IBTS; North Sea; species richness; temperature","abundance; biogeography; body size; community structure; demersal fish; fishing; global warming; marine environment; physiological response; population distribution; pressure effect; species richness; survey; Atlantic Ocean; North Sea",,,,,,"Overzicht der uitkomsten Van visscherijwaarnemingen met het S. S. Wodan: derde stuk: analyse der vangsten met de otter trawl in de jaren 1906 and 1907 (1908) Jaarboek Van Het Rijksinstituut voor Het Onderzoek der Zee, p. 73. , Anon; Visscherijwaarnemingen met de ""wodan"". Analyse der vangsten met de otter trawl in het jaar 1908 (1909) Jaarboek Van Het Rijksinstituut voor Het Onderzoek der Zee, p. 32. , Anon; Visscherijwaarnemingen met de ""wodan"". Analyse der vangsten met de otter trawl in het jaar 1909 (1910) Jaarboek Van Het Rijksinstituut voor Onderzoek der Zee, p. 37. , Anon; Trawling investigations, 1906-9. Fourth Report (Southern Area) on fishery and hydrographical investigations in the North Sea and adjacent waters (1912) Marine Biological Association of the UK, pp. 303-497. , Anon International Fisheries Investigations Darling & Son, London; Attrill, M.J., Power, M., Climatic influence on a marine fish assemblage (2002) Nature, 417 (6886), pp. 275-278. , DOI 10.1038/417275a; Bergmann, C., Uber die Verhältnisse der Wärmeökonomie der Thiere zu ihrer Grösse. (1847) Göttinger Studien, 3, pp. 595-708; Blanchard, J.L., Dulvy, N.K., Jennings, S., Ellis, J.R., Pinnegar, J.K., Tidd, A., Kell, L.T., Do climate and fishing influence size-based indicators of Celtic Sea fish community structure? (2005) ICES Journal of Marine Science, 62, pp. 405-411; Brander, K.M., Impacts of climate change on fisheries (2010) Journal of Marine Systems, 79, pp. 389-402; Brander, K.M., Blom, G., Borges, M.F., Erzini, K., Henderson, G., MacKenzie, B.R., Mendes, H., Changes in fish distribution in the eastern North Atlantic: Are we seeing a coherent response to changing temperature? (2003) ICES Marine Science Symposia, 219, pp. 261-270; Callaway, R., Engelhard, G.H., Dann, J., Cotter, J., Rumohr, H., A century of North Sea epibenthos and trawling: Comparison between 1902-1912, 1982-1985 and 2000 (2007) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 346, pp. 27-43. , DOI 10.3354/meps07038; Cheung, W.W.L., Lam, V.W.Y., Sarmiento, J.L., Kearny, K., Watson, R., Pauly, D., Projecting global marine biodiversity impacts under climate change scenarios (2009) Fish and Fisheries, 10, pp. 235-251; Daan, N., Spatial and temporal trends in species richness and abundance for the southerly and northerly components of the North Sea fish community separately, based on IBTS data 1977-2005 (2006) ICES Document CM 2006/D:02, p. 10; Daan, N., Gislason, H., Pope, J.G., Rice, J.C., Changes in the North Sea fish community: Evidence of indirect effects of fishing? (2005) ICES Journal of Marine Science, 62 (2), pp. 177-188. , DOI 10.1016/j.icesjms.2004.08.020; Daufresne, M., Lengfeller, K., Sommer, U., Global warming benefits the small in aquatic ecosystems (2009) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the USA, 106, pp. 12788-12793; Dulvy, N.K., Rogers, S.I., Jennings, S., Stelzenmuller, V., Dye, S.R., Skjoldal, H.R., Climate change and deepening of the North Sea fish assemblage: A biotic indicator of warming seas (2008) Journal of Applied Ecology, 45 (4), pp. 1029-1039. , DOI 10.1111/j.1365-2664.2008.01488.x; Enfield, D.B., Cid-Serrano, L., Secular and multidecadal warmings in the North Atlantic and their relationships with major hurricane activity (2010) International Journal of Climatology, 30, pp. 174-184; Engelhard, G.H., One hundred and twenty years of change in fishing power of English North Sea trawlers (2008) Advances in Fisheries Science 50 Years on from Beverton and Holt, pp. 1-25. , Ed. by A. Payne, J. Cotter, and T. Potter Wiley-Blackwell, Oxford, UK; E